<Review>This is a beautiful, shady, well-maintained park. I'm only knocking off a star because there are only three trash bins, and they are all at the front third of the park, closer to the entrance. There are also no bathrooms, so be sure to go beforehand. There is a creek bed running the length of the park and it was almost entirely dry (at least when I went, in late May). Shurtleff park is long, with a few branching paths, and completely gated - a great stop for an off-leash adventure.</Review>< pictures>
None<//pictures>

<name>Grant Wasson<//name><rate>5< /rate>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
<review>I claim to be no expert on anything but I've enjoyed sushi in different coastal establishments as well as some of the highest reviewed places in and around San Diego.  Ebisu is without a doubt my favorite.  Consistently wonderful every time.  Delicious, original creations as well as favorite standards.   The close attention to detail especially temperature are highlights.  You can't go wrong with anything here.  Delicious items for a non-fish eater as well such as grilled fare and wonderful veggie rolls.  Very friendly environment and staff.  Great for a romantic date night or a group looking for a fun time.  Try the stylish weekend-open lounge in the back which boasts a stocked bar with some excellent Japanese whiskies, thoughtful beer variety, many sakes, and other unique selections.  Ebisu is truly some of the best dining in San Diego.</review></record>

This is one of my go-to sushi spots. It's not the cheapest sushi in Hillcrest, but like everything else in life, you get what you pay for, and  Ebisu is more than worth a little more $$$.

<Date>1442945583609< /Date><rating>2< /rating><Text>Came here based on reviews and wanted to try a different sushi place than our usual.

Waitress was courteous and friendly but she was so soft spoken we could barely hear what she was saying to us.  The place wasn't noisy and I don't have a hearing problem so seriously please speak up next time.

Menu was interesting.  A lot of stuff we haven't seen at other sushi places.  We ordered the Tuna & Eggs, Blood Orange Hamachi Sashimi, "Pink Phloyd", and one more roll but I can't remember for the life of me.  Anyway, though everything sounded amazing it was mediocre by taste.  The "Pink Phloyd" is supposedly shiitake mushrooms, curry spicy tuna, with dried bonito, dashi sauce but all I tasted was chicken bouillon?!  The Tuna & Eggs was the dish I was most excited for but the quail egg was just on the side not on top of the sashimi like I thought it was.  I don't know it didn't seem creative at that point. Everything else was just okay.

Overall, pretty disappointment.  I like creativity but if the fish gets lost in all the crazy things added to it then...what's the point?  Anyway, food was alright but I think we're going to stick to our usual sushi places.<//Text>< pics>

<UserId.>109815267831202318650</UserId.><Pics>None</Pics><user_name>Walter Macalma</user_name>< date>
1402703925555</date>
<text>Boy do I feel like a brand noobian. I've been here 2-3 times over the years and never even knew they had a back room lounge/bar. WTF. How is that not in the highlights or tips and almost 500 reviews. Epic fail fellow yelpers, let me fix this. I've got an enormous bladder so never have to go to the bathroom and thus by reason for not going down the hallway and checking it out. I've also never been here latenight, so that's my fault.

Most of the other reviews will tell you of their great Happy Hour and garlic edamame which are both excellent and worth a try, but you should get bonito flakes on those garlic edamame's for some texture and too many aren't giving you the whole story here. Apps are pretty standard otherwise. Oysters are good, but pricey, even by the half dozen, plated a little too fancy as well. They really love their house salad because it's their base to other salads. The dressings are quite good, sesame-soy/lemon ginger is the highlight. Salmon skin is crispy and if you want more substance I prefer the tako to the tuna because the octopus to me takes on the marinade more than the tuna. I'm more used to the traditional Hawaiian style anyhow.

The garlic sauce for the soft shell crab is excellent and not bad on price, actually all the ponzu flavors as well are great for anything coming out of the kitchen. On the opposite end of the spectrum the supremely flavorful tuna collar dinner is to me almost not worth it. The collar is the rare instance where the most flavorful part of the fish is the cheapest and far too often discarded so the price point on this literally seems fishy, sure the yellowtail is extra thick and meaty, but when your amberjack fried and thinner grilled version are half, I have to question that. It's excellent if you don't mind the price. Thick, bursting with flavor and fat and with classic rice and salad it's a perfect meal. Jalapeno Hamachi sashimi is an interesting concept, but I think could be achieved differently and didn't wow me. Ankimo was well priced and often the base by which many traditional Japanese critics compare sushi restaurants. Liked how it was paired with wakame salad. Delicate and something I always suggest to people along with uni. Tempura Shrimp isn't a bad deal as they are large shrimp.

Omakase isn't quite what you're thinking. You only get it with the sashimi option versus the whole menu and to me they under value the option as a whole. The unagi is broiled, but thick and meaty, I was hoping for the smokey flavor from BBQ. Maki is very traditional and the standard nigiri line up with some extras like red snapper (ask for thinly sliced with a touch of lemon) mirugai, both rare even around SD. The specialty rolls are also not as adventurous as other places going overboard on ingredients and profiles, this is a good thing. The ponzu options make their sashimi menu very enticing.

Staff is very friendly as are the chef's, hours are great, especially Happy Hour. I've found people come here to drink more than eat in what is apparently the main room.

Ok so the back. Lounge holding 50 people with 2 booths and maybe 3 tables and the bar. Love the booth for the DJ and live bands that play. The key here is to try their extensive Japanese Whiskey collection, probably the biggest in SD, certainly more than the newer and supposedly Japanese menu influenced Bang Bang. They have more than just Hibiki here and the prices for drinks are very reasonable.  Service can be slow here because there is usually 1 bartender. Don't be like me and check this place out for all it's worth with great food and drink. It to me lacks in d√©cor and the bathrooms seem insufficient for the capacity and I was hoping for more izakaya options. Not a single don bowl,</text><Rating>4</Rating>< gmapID>
0x80d954c52d6d1fab:0x9a27e7c10aa0602d< /gmapID>

< review>
IF I COULD GIVE THIS PLACE 0 STARS, OR BETTER YET NEGATIVE STARS.. I WOULD! AVOID THIS PLACE AT ALL COSTS!

I'm writing this review because I'm appalled by how unprofessional & lack of respect this place, more specifically the owner/manager Sal has treated my former bride. Of all the weddings I've planned and coordinated, this is by far the worst experience I've witnessed.

My former bride (client) ordered her dream wedding dress months in advance, the sales associate as well as the owner/manager Sal all reassured her that she will receive her dress no later than May. Fast forward, May rolled around and still no dress in sight. Not once did they reach out to her to update her on the status of the dress, instead my former bride had to call in everyday just to check up on the status. Finally with just TWO weeks before the wedding, the dress finally arrived, leaving little to no time for her to get her alterations done. When things couldn't get any worse, it did!! They placed the order for the WRONG dress!!! She had originally ordered a mermaid style dress, instead a ball gown showed up.

Instead of owning up to their mistakes, they were being so rude and hostile to my client. The owner/manager Sal even had the audacity to tell her he'd give her money back and told her to go find a dress somewhere else. <user_id>106657027749217460223< /user_id>< user_name>
Chapi's Kitchen< /user_name>
<date>1605394851508< /date><Rate>5< /Rate><review>So glad to have an Aldi in the area! This was my store of choice while traveling through Europe. They have lots of normal items (produce, meat, snacks, frozen items) but also plenty of unique finds (European cookies, chocolate, cheese, alcohol I haven't seen elsewhere). You probably won't find everything you're looking for, but there are lots of great finds and the prices are quite low.
Tips for your visit:
CARTS: To get a cart you need to deposit 25 cents which will unlock it for use. When you return the cart, you get your quarter back. When I visited they had an employee giving out quarters to use, but I don't think that'll last forever.
BAGGING: When checking out, everything goes immediately into your cart, and then you walk to a counter where you can bag everything yourself. This helps the line to move quickly.
Favorite finds so far: brioche buns way cheaper than Sprouts (at the same quality), dark chocolate butter cookies from Germany, sangria that was surprisingly good, and a really dark pumpernickel bread.

Remember to shop local so you can support Poway! <3</review>< pics>

We've been with State Farm for over a couple of decades, primarily because of Steven Wang, and his friendly Staff.

From the moment we signed up for auto insurance, we've added many various lines over the years during our personal review of our situation along the timeline of this thing called life. Not only in the good times when we are on solid ground (knock on wood, as we're in Southern California!) but even when we've had a major claim on our home. We definitely appreciate the answers to our many questions during these moments and appreciate the human aspect Steven and his Staff exhibit towards my family.

We continue hitting new milestones and recently a major one happened: adding a teen driver to our policy (Yay! ...we now have a personal Uber driver!). Kimberly and Bima walked us through our options so we could choose the best route, while at the same time cross-checking our coverages to make sure the current situation matched our expectations for coverages. Just in this short duration of friendly conversation, we were able to discover yet another discount that we now qualified for (thanks, Kimberly and Bima, for taking the time to chat outside of the "just insure our son" scenario).

We've always felt welcome in working with Steven and his Staff, and we look forward to future conversations in many years to come!

My group enjoyed the food and complimentary chips. The service is very sub par. Even though there's a large menu on a screen, it's a sit down establishment. < Text>
I ordered the Pastor Super Burrito for $8.50 and was disappointed that there was more fat than meat. Waitress doesn't speak English very well so a bit hard to communicate if you don't speak Spanish. She was friendly though and service was pretty good. Was not crowded on a Wed. evening at 8:00pm. Atmosphere is better than most "authentic" Mexican food restaurants. Nice murals on the wall. Maybe another meat is better but I don't recommend the Pastor meat. Disappointing since the name of the place includes Pastor. If you like lots of fat and gristle in your food, you might like it better than me.< /Text>

<Rating>5<//Rating><text>This dental office is amazing.  My best friend of over 45 years recommended that my husband go there for a consultation.  Many other dentists have said that he was never going to be a candidate for full upper or any other type of implants.

We went to Anacapa Dental Art Institute and met with Dr. Saj Jivraj in early May.  Dr. Jivraj has a wonderful "chairside" manner and he said that he could help my husband.  This was such fabulous news; we were elated!

Dr. Jivraj explained in detail what needed to be done and now my husband is on the way to having his lovely smile fully restored as it was when we were much younger - thirty plus years ago.

We fully trust Dr. Jivraj and his team.  The women who run the front and back office are very outgoing, friendly, and extremely competent.   Anacapa Dental Art Institute office runs like a well oiled machine. We come from nearly 50 miles away, and they are more than happy to schedule appointments at our convenience.

<text>WARNING! The price Anacapa charges for full mouth implants is insanely higher than any other implant dentists I've yet inquired about, possibly the highest priced dentist currently practicing. I was quoted $51,000 dollars for their 'All on 4' procedure for myself, and I've been told by several local dentists (as well as Anacapa too) that I'm an excellent implant candidate with good jawbone and gums. They heavily advertise they can do this procedure in 1 day . . . do you think ANYONE deserves $51K for ONE day of work?

Please don't misunderstand my low score, the facility and staff are top notch. The moment I walked into their Ventura office, I knew immediately that they were going to be higher priced than most others. The facility is extremely impressive-the best of everything, all new and sparkly; the staff treats you like a celebrity; the doctor is renowned not only by his patients, but by his peers as well, according to their literature he lectures regularly and apparently is in high demand.

What I find disconcerting is the fact that the All on 4 procedure involves only 4 actual implants into your jaw, saving the patient countless hours and so much less pain and waiting and risk over the standard/classic 'one implant for every missing tooth' procedure that most implant dentists currently practice. Common sense would dictate they could charge substantially less just from the time commitment alone. And I have no problem paying a premium for his superior skill, excellent facilities and equipment, and the time and trouble they save you having everything 'in house', i.e. no subcontracting.

But $51 thousand dollars when I've been getting quotes running $10K to $15K less for the same end result? I guess I'm just the wrong demographic. Perhaps his office belongs in Beverly Hills or Pacific Palisades?</text><pictures>None< /pictures>< response>

<userid>113722796003708648764</userid>< user_name>
Wendy Holder</user_name>
<time>1520883171301< /time><Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
I did a lot of research before choosing Anacapa Dental Art Institute because I am terrified of going to the dentist.

My first visit, they gave me a tour of the facilities, took pictures of my mouth and Dr. Jivraj even fixed my broken front tooth!  No pain or anything.  They really understood my fears and really listened to me.

My next visit, they measured my mouth and took more pictures.  We talked about my treatment options (my mouth was a total mess) and the Dr.'s recommendations.  Because of Dr. Jivraj's extensive experience, he answered all of my questions and I felt very comfortable going with his recommendations.

The "BIG" day:  My husband brought me in and after the anesthesiologist put me under, they went to work.  It was a marathon, but they got so much done.  Not only did they pull my problem teeth, they also cleaned up a bunch of infections and even set the implants!  I was so surprised that they were able to do all of that.

So, now I am healing.  Let me tell you, there was no bruising and very little swelling (and I bruise very easily).  I figured I would look like a chipmunk, but that did not happen at all.  I am not sure how they managed that, but they did!  I have seen people after having one tooth pulled and they are miserable, all bruised and swollen.  I had 7 teeth pulled and am truly amazed.  My own mother did not see anything (and she notices EVERYTHING).

I will update this review as I progress through my treatment.  I hope this helps other people like me.  This is truly a great place!</Text>

< Review>
A few of my friends and I went out for a some dinner and drinks and found ourselves here. We sat right at the bar and ordered some appetizers to split between us as we had our drinks. The food was absolutely delicious! We had their fried calamari, prawn cocktail, and their sample platter. Everything was seasoned perfectly and the presentation was perfect. The bartender, Michelle, was very friendly and although it was a bit busy she was very attentive to our needs, always checking back in on us to see if we needed refills or anything else. The people we talked to were very friendly and I even bumped into someone from my town of Rio Vista. What a small world! Also, you cannot beat that waterfront view! :) Definitely coming back!</Review>

<user_id>117611413292783597234<//user_id><user_name>Melissa Odom<//user_name>< time>
1565585429133</time>
<Rating>2<//Rating>< Review>
My daughter and I looked up restaurants on the water in Vallejo and chose this one for the view and reviews. After looking over the menu my daughter asked if anything was prepared unbreaded and grilled only. The kind waitress said no, they could not make accommodations for any gluten or dairy allergies. She even went and ask the chef if he would make an exception and grill her seafood because she's allergic. He said no! So, she ordered a steak that wasn't well seasoned, nor very tender. It was over 27.00 and wasn't even good. My meal of seared scallops and prawns was okay but not worth the price paid. The waitress and server were good but I would not recommend this restaurant if you have any special dietary needs.< /Review>

< Text>

<user_name>Steven Marcotte</user_name><rate>4</rate><user_id>113136245779699328557< /user_id></record>
</dataset><record>
<userid>100578308237737103175</userid>< user_name>
Ted Giraldin</user_name>
< time>
1490720594403<//time>
< Resp>
None< /Resp>
< rate>
2</rate>
< Review>
This place is a perfect example an economic theory I like to call, "Tragedy of the Waterfront". There is something about waterfront places where they rely on the view and their location... and then they just stop trying as hard as they can.

This restaurant is tired. Just walking up to the property I wondered if this was a candidate for Gordon Ramsay's TV show "Kitchen Nightmares"? The hostess desk is replaced with a sign that tells you to stand by the fireplace if you want a table. This lackluster greeting was an accurate harbinger of the level of organization displayed by the staff.

The menu and the piano player had something in common... both were filled with unimaginative selections held over from the 70s and 80s.

Fried and sauteed seafood, though very fresh, was presented perfunctorily on china that must have been salvaged from the estate sales of eccentric grandmothers long since departed. Our order for a party of four didn't come to the table at the same time. One dish took several minutes longer while we graciously waited. If a server needs a moment to make two trips, that's understandable. But, leaving one person out, especially when the meals are all of "fry it and sauce it" complexity... not acceptable.

In the end, this is a place that's surviving... but sadly, not thriving.< /Review>

None<//pictures>
</record>

< Rate>
1</Rate>
<Response>None< /Response><review>I've never felt the need to write a review before my experience here. We reserved a table and when we arrived we were greeted at the fireplace in the middle of the room immediately and seated. Our waitress was the only other good thing at this place. We ordered our food including appetizers at 8:05 PM.

The restaurant closes at 9:00 PM, however around 8:20 PM the owners arrived and the atmosphere immediatly switched to everyone scrambling to clean tables, putting away dishes and counting the till. At 8:45 PM the couple seated next to us that arrived at 8:15 PM complained to the owner that they ordered appetizers. By 8:50 PM they 'd recieved their appetizers. My group didn't get our fried zucchini and calamira until 9 PM nearly an hour later. Our waitress could tell at this point everyone was pissed off and apologized for the wait before going back to cleaning.

At 9:30 We finally got our food. The steak was tasteless, tough and definitely not medium rare as specified. My girlfriend ordered the prime rib and thankfully it came with beef au jus which I spent the next 10 minutes dunking my $30steak into so I could eat it.

I'm guessing this place doesn't want to waste money on air conditioning because it was nearly 85¬∞ inside.

<time>1487143462926</time><user_name>Robb Sarmento</user_name><response>None< /response><GmapID>0x8085736192ea0f85:0x50d4c9455ad8fda9</GmapID>< Text>
The only reason I gave you one star is because you can't give a negitive 20 stars and this is why...

My girlfriend and I had the un pleasure of reserving a table at your establishment for your Valentine's dinner. As we arrived the place seemed Loud and crowded we had a 7 o'clock reservation and we're told it would be about 10 mins. to be seated so we went to the small cluttered bar I ordered a Cadillac Margarita and a double shot of crown royal these 2 drinks cost me 40 dollars....really..... shortly after receiving our extremely over priced drinks we were seated, the entire bar was brightly lit up with a very Loud somewhat intoxicated piano player in the corner. There was nothing remotely romantic about your bar nothing because this is what it felt like.  A over proceed unprofessional dive bar. My date and I sat alone at our brightly lit table listening to loud piano music for 20mins before anyone even acknowledged our existence at the table. When our server finally did arrive it was nearly impossible to hear her over the piano noise and surrounding banter of the other patrons. We ordered our food and then we sat there for another 45 mins without any contact with the server until she came to apologize but it would be another 10 to 15 min wait. So now we have been in your establishment for 1 full hour we've spent 40 dollars on 2 drinks and a small garden salad in a brightly lit extremely loud and extremely non romatic dive bar and literally 30 seconds before my date and I were going to just walk out because of the miserable abeyance and pitiful service, our food came my girlfriend had the salmon and seemed pleased with it I had the rack of lamb which was decently cooked nothing to write home about but never the less it was accompanied by baby carrots and cold potatoes otherwise very disappointing.  She had dessert and I choose to pass because literally I couldn't wait to get out of there and honestly for a bar of your caliber on any given night I would have chaulked it up as just other night out at a dive bar with no professionalism at all and went on with my night, but tonight was Valentine's day and I've never been more embarrassed in my life, i promised my girlfriend a romantic evening and all i got for $150.00 was alot of noise, bad service over priced drinks and brite lights. I vow to never set foot in your bar again and i will make it my calling to share my opinion about your bar and it's lack of service every chance i get. The only advice i can give you is to never try pulling a romantic evening dinner off there ever again because frankly you have no idea what you are doing. Thank you for the worst Valentine's Ever.

Yours Reluctantly ,
Robb Sarmento<//Text>
